SIMPLE: estimable
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Estimable
<hw>Es"ti*ma*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>estimable</ets>, or L. <ets>aestimabilis</ets>. See
<er>Esteem</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Capable of being estimated or
valued; <as>as, <ex>estimable</ex> damage</as>.</def> <rj><au>Paley.
.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Valuable; worth a great price.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A pound of man's flesh, taken from a man,⟦br⟧
Is not so <qex>estimable</qex>, profitable neither,⟦br⟧
As flesh of muttons, beefs, or goats.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Worth of esteem or respect; deserving our good
opinion or regard.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A lady said of her two companions, that one was more amiable, the
other more <qex>estimable</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Estimable</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Estimable
<hw>Es"ti*ma*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A thing worthy of
regard.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One of the peculiar <qex>estimables</qex> of her country.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Estimableness</ent>⟦br⟧
